It can contain contact lists, task lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify all available on one browser at the same time.
What is unique about the personal data warehouse on the Internet is that it only depends on the user who has access to certain types of information.
The company calls it “personal data-enhancing.”
Inrapt’s idea, according to CEO John Bruce, is the company to provide resources, process and appropriate skills for Solid to be available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform bought by IBM, several development developers with a contract to work on the project, and a community of coders-volunteers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on Inrapt’s web site.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether to introduce a complete change where their business models are completely turned upside down overnight.
“We don’t ask for their permission.”
In a press release on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrapt's mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that will help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on the basis of Solid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by founding the Consortium of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's World Wide Web.
Recently, Berners-Lee has been an influential speaker in the debate on net neutrality.
Even at the start of Inrapt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the Consortium of the World Network, the Internet Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m a big optimist for the new era on the Internet,” Berners-Lee added.
