Then a map of habitats will be created to create a detailed picture of their behavior in the area.
Rob Dever, nature conservation advisor at En-Ty-Es, hopes the results will reveal which areas of life are most important to the lily and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forests for lilys and other related species.
The population of lilacs in Scotland and Britain has declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by the construction and development that affect the beds and the loss of habitats.
Veterinarians and lights also pose a risk, as well as adhesive tapes for flies and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks on domestic cats.
Lilacs aren't really blind.
However, due to their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to capturing prey.
They use sophisticated eco-location techniques to find insects and obstacles in the path of flight.
En-Tie-es, which takes care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes the lilies very seriously.
There are ten trained experts, who regularly conduct research, bed inspections, and sometimes rescues.
The organisation even established the first and only reserves for lilacs in Scotland on the Triv estate in Damfris and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten species living in Scotland.
Property manager David Thomson says the property is an ideal territory for them.
“We have an excellent area for lilys here in Triv,” he said.
“We have old buildings, very old two and very good living quarters.
But there are a lot of unknown things about the lilies, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us learn more about what they need to progress.”
He stressed that it is important to check whether there are lilacs before renovating the properties because the unconscious destruction of beds can destroy up to 400 women and infants, and destroy the entire local population.
Lilies are protected and it is illegal to kill, torture or disturb or destroy their beds.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer in the Lilies Protection Trust, encourages the public to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about the lilies and our other species, we just don’t know how they live.”
